            <p class="blog-lead">
                Your email client just rejected your attachment, or it's been
                sitting on "sending" for five minutes. Here are four ways to
                get a large PDF to its destination, from fastest to most
                reliable.
            </p>

            <h2>Why your PDF won't attach</h2>
            <p>
                Most providers cap attachments well below what a PDF can
                actually reach. Gmail and Yahoo Mail limit attachments to
                25MB, Outlook to 20MB. Scanned documents, presentations
                exported to PDF, and reports with embedded charts routinely
                exceed these limits — sometimes by a wide margin.
            </p>

            <h2>Option 1: Compress the PDF</h2>
            <p>
                The fastest fix if your file is only somewhat over the limit.
                Compression downsamples embedded images and strips redundant
                data without converting the file or changing its format.
                A 40MB scanned document can often drop to under 10MB.
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to <a href="/compress-pdf">PdfToolStack Compress PDF</a></li>
                <li>Upload the file and choose a compression level</li>
                <li>Download the compressed PDF and attach it as normal</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                If the file is still too large afterward, combine this with
                one of the methods below.
            </p>

            <h2>Option 2: Split the PDF into smaller files</h2>
            <p>
                For long documents — reports, manuals, scanned books — splitting
                into sections often makes more sense than compressing a single
                giant file. Each part stays under the attachment limit and the
                recipient can open exactly the section they need.
            </p>
            <p>
                Use <a href="/split-pdf">PDF Splitter</a> to break the document
                into page ranges, then send each part as a separate attachment
                or in separate emails.
            </p>

            <h2>Option 3: Use a cloud storage link instead</h2>
            <p>
                For files that are simply too large to email no matter how much
                you compress them — large scanned archives, high-resolution
                design files — upload to Google Drive, Dropbox, or OneDrive and
                share a link instead of an attachment. Most email clients will
                even suggest this automatically once a file is too big.
            </p>
            <p>
                Set the link to expire or restrict access if the document
                contains sensitive information.
            </p>

            <h2>Option 4: Use a dedicated file transfer service</h2>
            <p>
                Services like WeTransfer or Smash let you send files up to
                several gigabytes without needing a cloud storage account.
                The recipient gets a download link by email. This works well
                for one-off transfers but isn't ideal for files you need to
                keep organized long-term.
            </p>

            <h2>Which method should you use?</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Slightly over the limit:</strong> Compress the PDF — quickest, no extra steps for the recipient</li>
                <li><strong>Long document:</strong> Split into sections, send the relevant part</li>
                <li><strong>Very large file, ongoing access needed:</strong> Cloud storage link</li>
                <li><strong>One-off, very large transfer:</strong> A file transfer service</li>
            </ul>

